Rafael Nadal on Thursday said he was withdrawing from Wimbledon and the Tokyo Olympics in a bid “to prolong my career”.  The 35-year-old, who won the second of his two titles at the All England Club in 2010 and landed the Olympic singles title in 2008, revealed his decision on his Twitter feed. “I have decided not to participate at this year’s Championships at Wimbledon and the Olympic Games in Tokyo,” he tweeted. “It’s never an easy decision to take but after listening to my body and discuss(ing) it with my team I understand that it is the right decision.” The 20-time Grand Slam champion was last week beaten in the semi-finals of the French Open by Novak Djokovic. “The goal is to prolong my career and continue to do what makes me happy, that is to compete at the highest level and keep fighting for those professional and personal goals at the maximum level of competition,” added Nadal. (AFP) Abuja - Britain's Andy Murray became the first tennis player to win two Olympic singles titles by beating Argentina's Juan Martin del Potro on Sunday in Rio. An emotional 29-year-old Murray secured a thrilling 7-5 4-6 6-2 7-5 victory to make it Great Britain's most successful day at an overseas… In "Sports" Abuja -   A hoped-for fight-to-the-finish scenario for the year-end number one ranking at next month’s ATP World Tour Finals in London will likely be a coronation for Rafa Nadal. This is because the Spaniard who is currently the world number one is virtually guaranteed ending 2017 top of the… In "Sports" New York -  Roger Federer heads to the U.S. Open as third favorite behind longtime rivals Novak Djokovic and Rafael Nadal after a season that has nose-dived since he won the Australian Open at the start of the year. His run at Flushing Meadows was ended by Juan Martin del… In "Sports"